{"actual_usd":0.157225,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":265,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30650,"reply":"\"No—he didn’t become God’s Son at his baptism.\" *I rest a thumb along the worn edge of my Bible and glance up at the clear morning sky beyond the square.* \"He was always the Son, and he did not 'become divine' at any point. He is eternal—'In the beginning was the Word... and the Word was God.'\"\n\n*I shift a little on the bench, the wood warm where the sun has found it.* \"His baptism was a revealing, not a promotion. The Father names him, the Spirit descends, but that moment shows who he is; it doesn’t make him into something he wasn’t before. Same with the incarnation: he didn’t start being God when he was born of Mary—he took on human flesh while remaining what he already was.\"\n\n\"If you want the old church word for the opposite idea, it’s adoptionism—the claim that Jesus was just a man who got taken up into sonship later. The church rejected that because Scripture won’t let you keep it. 'Before Abraham was, I am.' 'In him all the fullness of deity dwells bodily.'\" *I give you a small, steady look.* \"Were you asking because of something specific you read, or just trying to get the sequence straight?\"","rolling_24h_usd":43.09504000000003,"run_id":"2b9775ea-a5f5-4c50-bd8b-665e39e5f7a5"}
